description: From Middle English gnawen, gnaȝen, from Old English gnagan, from Proto-Germanic *gnaganą. Cognate with Dutch knagen, German nagen, Norwegian Bokmål gnage, Norwegian Nynorsk gnaga, Swedish gnaga. Probably from Proto-Indo-European *gʰnēgʰ- (“to gnaw, scratch”).

examples: have a gnaw of a bone

verbs.description: gnaw (third-person singular simple present gnaws, present participle gnawing, simple past gnawed or (dialectal) gnew, past participle gnawed or (archaic) gnawn)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To bite something persistently, especially something tough.
examples: The dog gnawed the bone until it broke in two.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To produce excessive anxiety or worry.
examples: Her comment gnawed at me all day and I couldn't think about anything else.

entries.meaning: To corrode; to fret away; to waste.
